  "prompt": "What is GST? How is it different from CST and VAT?",
  "response": "GST (Goods and Services Tax), CST (Central Sales Tax), and VAT (Value Added Tax) are different types of indirect taxes in India. Let me explain each of them:\n\nGST (Goods and Services Tax):\n1. Implemented in India from July 1, 2017\n2. Comprehensive, multi-stage tax covering most goods and services\n3. Replaced multiple indirect taxes\n4. Unified tax system across the country\n5. Follows destination-based taxation\n6. Rates are uniform across states\n7. Input tax credit is available\n8. Aim to reduce tax cascading and simplify taxation\n\nVAT (Value Added Tax):\n1. Existed before GST implementation\n2. State-level tax on sale of goods\n3. Different rates in different states\n4. Applicable only to goods\n5. Limited input tax credit\n6. Complex tax structure\n\nCST (Central Sales Tax):\n1. Levied on inter-state sale of goods\n2. Collected by the selling state\n3. Charged on goods moving between states\n4. Existed before GST implementation\n5. Rates varied between states\n\nKey Differences:\n- GST is a comprehensive tax system\n- VAT was state-level taxation\n- CST was specific to inter-state sales\n- GST has largely replaced both VAT and CST",
